For any type A we have a proposition \mathsf {toProp}\,{A} equipped with a unit map \eta _{\mathsf {prop}}\colon  A \to \mathsf {toProp}\,{A}; moreover, we have the following induction principle: for any family of propositions B\colon  \mathsf {toProp}\,A \to  \mathsf {Prop}, any function b\colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} B
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _{\mathsf {prop}}\,x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 extends to a function b^\sharp  \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\colon \mathsf {toProp}\,A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\colon \mathsf {toProp}\,A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\colon \mathsf {toProp}\,A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\colon \mathsf {toProp}\,A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} Bx.

For any precategory C, the type \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D : \mathsf {Precategory}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
